Instead of defining our own `Enumerable`/`Enumerator` interfaces, why not build on ECMAScript 2015's `Iterable`/`Iterator` protocols?

 - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Iteration_protocols
 - https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/blob/342616781e80202f40872f044605806ba73837a3/src/lib/es2015.iterable.d.ts

```typescript
interface IteratorResult<T> {
    done: boolean;
    value: T;
}

interface Iterator<T> {
    next(value?: any): IteratorResult<T>;
    return?(value?: any): IteratorResult<T>;
    throw?(e?: any): IteratorResult<T>;
}

interface Iterable<T> {
    [Symbol.iterator](): Iterator<T>;
}
```

Then we could define our own `QueryableIterable<T>` and `QueryableIterablePromise<T>` interfaces that extend these to hang the query functions on.

